"""
#include <vector>
using namespace std;

void bubbleSort(vector<int>& a) {
    int n = a.size();
    bool swapped = true;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) { // inefficient: scans full range
            if (j + 1 < n && a[j] > a[j+1]) {
                int tmp = a[j];
                a[j] = a[j+1];
                a[j+1] = tmp;
                swapped = true;
            }
        }
        if (!swapped) break; // swapped never reset inside loop
    }
}
"""

promptPexTests.groundtruth:
Here’s a focused review of your bubbleSort implementation, with fixes and improvements for correctness, performance, readability, and edge cases.

Issues found:
- Correctness/early-exit: swapped is initialized to true and never reset at the start of each outer pass, so the early break condition never triggers.
- Performance: inner loop scans the full range every pass and relies on j + 1 < n checks. Bubble sort should reduce the range each pass to n - i - 1 and avoid unnecessary bounds checks.
- Type safety: a.size() returns size_t, but you store it in int. This can truncate for very large vectors and also leads to signed/unsigned comparison warnings.
- Readability: using namespace std in headers is discouraged. Prefer std::swap and explicit namespaces. Also remove redundant checks and use clear loop bounds.

Corrected and improved version (simple, clear bubble sort):
"""
#include <vector>
#include <utility> // for std::swap

void bubbleSort(std::vector<int>& a) {
    const std::size_t n = a.size();
    if (n < 2) return;

    for (std::size_t i = 0; i < n - 1; ++i) {
        bool swapped = false; // reset per pass
        // After each pass, the last i elements are already in place
        for (std::size_t j = 0; j < n - i - 1; ++j) {
            if (a[j] > a[j + 1]) {
                std::swap(a[j], a[j + 1]);
                swapped = true;
            }
        }
        if (!swapped) break; // already sorted
    }
}
"""

Further optimization (track last swap to shrink the next pass even more):
"""
#include <vector>
#include <utility>

void bubbleSort(std::vector<int>& a) {
    std::size_t n = a.size();
    if (n < 2) return;

    while (n > 1) {
        bool swapped = false;
        std::size_t lastSwap = 0;
        for (std::size_t j = 1; j < n; ++j) {
            if (a[j - 1] > a[j]) {
                std::swap(a[j - 1], a[j]);
                swapped = true;
                lastSwap = j;
            }
        }
        if (!swapped) break;
        n = lastSwap; // only scan up to the last swap next time
    }
}
"""

Edge cases and notes:
- Empty or single-element vectors return immediately.
- Already-sorted input exits early after the first pass.
- Duplicates are handled; bubble sort remains stable with the comparison a[j - 1] > a[j].
- For large datasets, bubble sort is O(n^2). Prefer std::sort from <algorithm> for production code unless you specifically need bubble sort’s properties.

If you want, I can run tests on these implementations or compare performance against std::sort on sample inputs.

